{
  "text": "Imaging is an effective way to clinically follow women who had hypertensive disorders during pregnancy to assess vascular dysfunction. Women who developed preeclampsia displayed increased carotid intima-media thickness (i.e., wall thickness) measured 3 months postpartum [CITATION_1] , and this changed persisted 12-24 months postpartum [CITATION_2] . In agreement with these findings, in Chile, a study including 217 women (average age 60 years), who presented coronary artery disease, reported that this condition presents earlier and was more severe, in women with a previous history of hypertension in pregnancy than in women with a previous normotensive pregnancy [CITATION_3] . Twenty-eight percent of women who had history of hypertension in pregnancy also had coronary stenosis 10 years after delivery, compared with 22% of normotensive women (P = 0.03). They also reported that the odd ratio for coronary artery disease was non-significant when previous history of hypertension in pregnancy was considered 2-ME 2-methoxyestradiol, ADA adenosine deaminase, BDNF brain-derived neurotrophic factor, FAAH fatty acid amide hydrolase, GH gestational hypertension, hsCRP high sensitive c-reactive protein, IL-1\u03b2 interleukin 1 beta, METRN meteorin, MMP matrix metalloproteinases, NAPE-PLD N-arachidonoyl phosphatidylethanolamine phospholipase D, NF-\u03bab nuclear factor kappa b, NHE-3 Na",
